   </tbody>
   <tfoot> </tfoot>
  </table>
  <p class="firstLine">
   A <mark>two-dimensional array</mark>
   (2D) is a block of memory, visualized as a table with rows and columns. In C++
   this is implemented (under the hood) by creating a <b>1D</b>
   array whose elements are, themselves, also <b>1D</b> arrays.
  </p>

  <p>Examine this code:</p>
  <table class="array" style="float:right;">
   <thead>
    <th style="width:25px;">&nbsp;</th><th>0</th><th>1</th><th>2</th>
   </thead>
   <tbody>
    <tr>
     <th>0</th><td>5</td><td>19</td><td>3</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <th>1</th><td>22</td><td>-8</td><td>10</td>
    </tr>
   </tbody>
   <tfoot> </tfoot>
  </table>
  <pre
   class="language-cpp line-numbers"
   style="width:60%;"><code>int a2d[2][3]; // a2d is a 2D array

a2d[0][0] = 5;
a2d[0][1] = 19;
a2d[0][2] = 3;
a2d[1][0] = 22;
a2d[1][1] = -8;
a2d[1][2] = 10;</code></pre>
  <p>
   It is easiest to think of <tt>a2d</tt>
   as containing <strong>two rows</strong> and
   <strong>three columns</strong>: a <tt>2</tt>
   <tt>Ã—</tt>
   <tt>3</tt> array. To access an element of a <b>2D</b> array, use <strong
    >two subscripts</strong
   >. The first is the <mark>row</mark>, the second is the <mark>column</mark>.
   Both are zero-based. On line 6, for instance, the first index (here <tt>1</tt
   >) signifies the second row and the second index (here
   <tt>0</tt>) denotes the column within the array.
  </p>
 </div>
</Layout>
